𝟏. 𝐈𝐧𝐝𝐞𝐧𝐭𝐚𝐭𝐢𝐨𝐧

In the vi or vim editor, you can use the following shortcuts to indent lines of code or text:
-----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Indenting a Single Line:
Place the cursor on the line you want to indent and press >> to indent it to the right.
To indent it to the left, press <<.

---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Indenting Multiple Lines:
First, enter Visual Line mode by pressing V.
Use the arrow keys or j/k to select the lines you want to indent.
Press > to indent the selected lines to the right.
Press < to indent the selected lines to the left.
-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Indenting with a Specific Number of Spaces:
You can also specify the number of spaces to indent. For example, to indent a line by 3 spaces, you can type 3>> while the cursor is on the line.
  
Using the Command Mode:
You can also use command mode to indent a range of lines. For example, to indent lines 10 to 20, you can type:

:10,20>
  
To indent them back to the left, you can use:

:10,20<
----------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Auto-Indenting:
If you want to auto-indent the entire file, you can use the command:

gg=G
  
This command will go to the beginning of the file (gg), auto-indent the current line (=), and then go to the end of the file (G).
These shortcuts should help you manage indentation effectively in vi or vim.

